\begin_layout Title
An Algorithm for the Quantification of the Signal Quality in Electrocardiograms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author

\lang spanish
Andrés Demski and Mariano Llamedo Soria
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Electronic Department, Universidad Tecnológica Nacional, Buenos Aires, Argentina
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
The electrocardiogram (ECG) recording is commonly corrupted by several sources
 of noise or interfering signals.
 It is very important to quantify the quality of the ECG recordings for
 reducing the automatic systems mistakes and false alarms.
 This topic has been already discussed during the PhysioNet/Computing in
 Cardiology Challenge 2011, where the best performing algorithms served
 as starting point to our work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
In this work we present an approach for ECG quality quantification based
 on a combination of a binary tree and signal quality indexes (SQI).
 The binary tree is responsible of detecting coarse interferences such as
 flatlines and high energy noise.
 If the binary tree classifies a record as acceptable, then a finer analysis
 is performed using a detector based on the SQI features.
 The SQI detector is based on a support vector machine with a Gaussian kernel.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
The performance of the algorithms was assessed using accuracy, sensitivity
 and specificity metrics.
 The bad quality detection performance obtained in this work reaches a 93%
 of accuracy, a 98% of sensitivity and a 76% of specificity.
 The results are promising and the SQI detector is a starting point for
 future improvement and further evaluation of the capability of generalisation
 to other databases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The electrocardiogram (ECG) is a routine and inexpensive technique to analyse
 the heart function.
 An ECG recording is commonly corrupted by several sources of noise or interferi
ng signals, such as power line, skeletal muscle activity, electrode movement
 or disconnection, among others.
 The automatic processing algorithms, such as heartbeat detectors and classifier
s, wave delineators, among others, are sensitive to the signal quality of
 the ECG.
 This makes important for the automatic systems to be able for quantifying
 the quality of the ECG, in order to minimise the algorithms error rate,
 discard unusable segments from longterm recordings, or discard corrupted
 records from databases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This topic was discussed during the PhysioNet/Computing in Cardiology Challenge
 2011 where the aim was to develop an efficient algorithm able to run in
 a mobile phone and provide useful feedback about the quality of the ECG
 for interpretation.
 The algorithm of this challenge should match the opinions of a group of
 human reviewers, who have classified each record as “acceptable” or “unacceptab
le.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our objective is to study an ECG quality detector, based on the best ranked
 works presented in the challenge 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "chengyu-cinc,dieter-cinc,clifford-quality-cinc"

\end_inset

.
 Our approach consists in a 2 level detector using first a binary tree as
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "chengyu-cinc,dieter-cinc"

\end_inset

, followed by an SQI approach as presented in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "clifford-quality-cinc"

\end_inset

.
 Finally, we are going to evaluate each detector individually and the joint
 performance for comparing with the CinC Challenge results.
\end_layout

