\begin_layout Subsection
Database
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this work we used the database of the Physionet/Computing in Cardiology
 Challenge 2011 (ecgqdb) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PhysioNet"

\end_inset

 and the MIT-BIH database arrhythmia (mitdb)
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MITBIHDB"

\end_inset

 .
 The ecgqdb includes 1000 ten-seconds records of 12-leads, sampled at 500
 Hz with 16 bits and 
\begin_inset Formula $5\,\mu V$
\end_inset

 of resolution.
 The database includes 773 acceptable and 225 unacceptable quality recordings.
 The mitdb includes 48 recordings of 30 minutes length, sampled at 360 Hz
 with 11 bits and 
\begin_inset Formula $5\,\mu V$
\end_inset

 resolution with a slew rate of 
\begin_inset Formula $225\,\nicefrac{mV}{sec}$
\end_inset

.
 The training set included part of the ecgqdb and the mitdb, while the ecgqdb
 was used for testing purposes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Proposed algorithm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We identified three important causes that are present in the unacceptable
 recordings: 1) flatlines, 2) spikes and 3) steps.
 For detecting that, we decided to develop three detectors with low computationa
l cost.
 Then a finer detection is performed using feature extraction and a machine
 learning algorithm.
 
\end_layout

